  <div class="components-layout">
    <main class="main-panel">
      <div class="page-header-area">
        <h1 class="page-title">LLM Reference</h1>
        <p class="page-desc">How to expose the Prism design system to LLMs so they generate spec-compliant, token-aware UI code every time.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="main-content-area">
        <div class="main-content-inner">

          <!-- Intro -->
          <div class="doc-section" style="margin-top: 16px;">
            <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.7; color: var(--prism-text-muted); max-width: 760px;">LLMs write code that looks correct but doesn't follow design systems. They invent colors, skip tokens, hardcode spacing, and ignore component APIs. This page documents the three-layer approach that fixes this — getting AI-generated UI to be Prism-compliant by default.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="tldr-box">
            <div class="tldr-label">TL;DR</div>
            <ul>
              <li>LLMs don't know your design system unless you tell them explicitly.</li>
              <li>Three-layer solution: <strong>spec files</strong> for components, <strong>semantic tokens</strong> for design decisions, <strong>audit scripts</strong> to verify compliance.</li>
              <li>Feed spec files + token files into every LLM prompt — or wire them into your IDE context.</li>
              <li>Pair with audit scripts to catch regressions before they ship.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>

          <hr class="doc-divider" />

          <!-- The Problem -->
          <div class="doc-section">
            <h2 id="the-problem" class="doc-section-title">The problem with LLMs and design systems</h2>
            <p class="doc-section-subtitle">LLMs are trained on vast amounts of generic code. That makes them good at writing React, HTML, and CSS — but not at following your specific system.</p>

            <p style="font-size: 15px; color: var(--prism-text-muted); line-height: 1.7; max-width: 760px; margin-bottom: 20px;">When you ask an LLM to "build a settings panel", it will:</p>

            <table class="size-table">
              <thead>
                <tr>
                  <th>What you expect</th>
                  <th>What you get</th>
                </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr>
                  <td><code style="font-family:monospace; background:rgba(34,197,94,0.08); color:#22c55e; padding:2px 8px; border-radius:6px; font-size:13px;">--prism-text-muted</code> for secondary text</td>
                  <td>Hardcoded <code style="font-family:monospace; font-size:13px;">#9ca3af</code> or <code style="font-family:monospace; font-size:13px;">gray-400</code></td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><code style="font-family:monospace; background:rgba(34,197,94,0.08); color:#22c55e; padding:2px 8px; border-radius:6px; font-size:13px;">&lt;Button variant="primary"&gt;</code></td>
                  <td>Custom <code style="font-family:monospace; font-size:13px;">&lt;button style="background:blue"&gt;</code></td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>Spacing using <code style="font-family:monospace; background:rgba(34,197,94,0.08); color:#22c55e; padding:2px 8px; border-radius:6px; font-size:13px;">--spacing-3</code></td>
                  <td>Inline <code style="font-family:monospace; font-size:13px;">padding: 12px</code></td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>Accessible label + input pairing</td>
                  <td>Unlabelled input with <code style="font-family:monospace; font-size:13px;">placeholder</code> only</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>Dark mode via CSS variables</td>
                  <td>No dark mode or duplicate class overrides</td>
                </tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>

            <div class="problem-callout" style="margin-top: 24px;">
              <p><strong>The root cause:</strong> LLMs don't fail because they're bad at coding. They fail because they don't know what <em>your</em> system looks like. Without context, they fall back to generic patterns from their training data.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <hr class="doc-divider" />

          <!-- Three-layer solution -->
          <div class="doc-section">
            <h2 id="three-layer-solution" class="doc-section-title">The three-layer solution</h2>
            <p class="doc-section-subtitle">Structured context at three levels makes LLMs generate Prism-compliant code reliably.</p>

            <div class="layer-grid">
              <div class="layer-card">
                <div class="layer-number">Layer 01</div>
                <div class="layer-title">Spec files</div>
                <div class="layer-desc">Markdown files that describe each component — its API, variants, anatomy, usage rules, and do/don't guidance. LLMs consume these as system prompts.</div>
              </div>
              <div class="layer-card">
                <div class="layer-number">Layer 02</div>
                <div class="layer-title">Token layer</div>
                <div class="layer-desc">A structured map of semantic design tokens — colors, spacing, radius, elevation — tied to their CSS variable names and intent. Prevents hardcoded values.</div>
              </div>
              <div class="layer-card">
                <div class="layer-number">Layer 03</div>
                <div class="layer-title">Audit scripts</div>
                <div class="layer-desc">Static analysis tools that scan generated code for compliance violations: hardcoded hex values, unknown components, missing token usage.</div>
              </div>
            </div>

            <h3 id="layer-1-spec" class="doc-h3">Layer 1 — Spec files</h3>
            <p class="doc-section-subtitle">Every Prism component has a <code style="font-family:monospace; font-size:13px;">.md</code> spec file that documents it for both humans and LLMs. These files follow a consistent structure:</p>

            <div class="code-block">
<span class="code-comment"># component-name.md structure</span>

<span class="code-key">## Overview</span>
Short description of what the component is and its primary use case.

<span class="code-key">## Anatomy</span>
Named breakdown of each part — root, trigger, content, arrow, etc.

<span class="code-key">## Variants / Props</span>
Every supported variant with accepted values and defaults.

<span class="code-key">## Token mapping</span>
Which CSS variables control each visual property.

<span class="code-key">## Usage rules</span>
When to use this component, when not to, and accessibility requirements.

<span class="code-key">## Do / Don't</span>
Concrete examples of correct vs. incorrect usage.
            </div>

            <p style="font-size: 14px; color: var(--prism-text-muted); line-height: 1.65; margin-top: 16px; max-width: 760px;">Spec files live alongside component source and are checked in to version control. When a component changes, the spec changes too. This keeps LLM context in sync with the actual system.</p>

            <h3 id="layer-2-tokens" class="doc-h3">Layer 2 — Token layer</h3>
            <p class="doc-section-subtitle">Semantic tokens are the bridge between design intent and code. A token file tells the LLM: "use <code style="font-family:monospace; font-size:13px;">--prism-text-muted</code> for secondary text" instead of a raw hex value.</p>

            <div class="code-block">
<span class="code-comment">/* prism-tokens.css — excerpt */</span>

<span class="code-key">:root</span> {
  <span class="code-comment">/* Text */</span>
  --prism-text:            rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.92);
  --prism-text-muted:      rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.48);

  <span class="code-comment">/* Surfaces */</span>
  --prism-surface:         rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.05);
  --prism-surface-hover:   rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.09);

  <span class="code-comment">/* Brand */</span>
  --prism-violet:          <span class="code-string">#2563eb</span>;
  --prism-cyan:            <span class="code-string">#06b6d4</span>;

  <span class="code-comment">/* Spacing */</span>
  --spacing-1: 4px;   --spacing-2: 8px;
  --spacing-3: 12px;  --spacing-4: 16px;
  --spacing-6: 24px;  --spacing-8: 32px;
}
            </div>

            <p style="font-size: 14px; color: var(--prism-text-muted); line-height: 1.65; margin-top: 16px; max-width: 760px;">Feed this token file into every LLM session as part of your system prompt. The model learns to reach for tokens first, not raw values.</p>

            <h3 id="layer-3-audit" class="doc-h3">Layer 3 — Audit scripts</h3>
            <p class="doc-section-subtitle">Audit scripts are the safety net. They scan generated or committed code for violations and surface them before they reach production.</p>

            <div class="code-block">
<span class="code-comment"># prism-audit.sh — example checks</span>

<span class="code-comment"># 1. Detect hardcoded hex colors not matching Prism palette</span>
grep -rn <span class="code-string">'#[0-9a-fA-F]\{3,6\}'</span> src/ | grep -v <span class="code-string">'prism-tokens'</span>

<span class="code-comment"># 2. Find inline style padding/margin not using tokens</span>
grep -rn <span class="code-string">'style=".*padding:.*[0-9]px'</span> src/

<span class="code-comment"># 3. Check for components used outside Prism component set</span>
grep -rn <span class="code-string">'&lt;button '</span> src/ | grep -v <span class="code-string">'Button'</span>
            </div>

            <p style="font-size: 14px; color: var(--prism-text-muted); line-height: 1.65; margin-top: 16px; max-width: 760px;">Run these in CI on every pull request. Violations fail the build. This creates a feedback loop that trains both LLMs and engineers to stay within the system.</p>
          </div>

          <hr class="doc-divider" />

          <!-- File Hierarchy -->
          <div class="doc-section">
            <h2 id="file-hierarchy" class="doc-section-title">File hierarchy</h2>
            <p class="doc-section-subtitle">The Prism repository is organized so that LLMs can locate context quickly. Every component lives alongside its spec, and tokens are centralized at the root.</p>

            <div class="file-tree" id="fileTree">

              <!-- Root -->
              <div class="ft-root">
                <span class="ft-icon ft-folder-icon">
                  <svg width="16" height="16" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.8"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M3 7a2 2 0 012-2h4l2 2h8a2 2 0 012 2v9a2 2 0 01-2 2H5a2 2 0 01-2-2V7z"/></svg>
                </span>
                <span class="ft-name ft-folder-name">Prism Design System</span>
              </div>

              <!-- specs/ -->
              <div class="ft-children">
                <div class="ft-row ft-folder-row" data-tree="specs">
                  <span class="ft-chevron">▶</span>
                  <span class="ft-icon ft-folder-icon">
                    <svg width="15" height="15" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.8"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M3 7a2 2 0 012-2h4l2 2h8a2 2 0 012 2v9a2 2 0 01-2 2H5a2 2 0 01-2-2V7z"/></svg>
                  </span>
                  <span class="ft-name ft-folder-name">specs/</span>
                </div>
                <div class="ft-subtree" id="specs">

                  <!-- foundations/ -->
                  <div class="ft-row ft-folder-row" data-tree="ft-foundations">
                    <span class="ft-chevron">▶</span>
                    <span class="ft-icon ft-folder-icon">
                      <svg width="15" height="15" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.8"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M3 7a2 2 0 012-2h4l2 2h8a2 2 0 012 2v9a2 2 0 01-2 2H5a2 2 0 01-2-2V7z"/></svg>
                    </span>
                    <span class="ft-name ft-folder-name">foundations/</span>
                    <span class="ft-badge ft-badge-1">Tier 1 — Visual primitives</span>
                  </div>
                  <div class="ft-subtree" id="ft-foundations">
                    <div class="ft-row ft-file-row"><span class="ft-icon ft-md-icon"><svg width="13" height="13" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M9 12h6m-6 4h6m2 5H7a2 2 0 01-2-2V5a2 2 0 012-2h5.586a1 1 0 01.707.293l5.414 5.414a1 1 0 01.293.707V19a2 2 0 01-2 2z"/></svg></span><span class="ft-name">color.md</span></div>
                    <div class="ft-row ft-file-row"><span class="ft-icon ft-md-icon"><svg width="13" height="13" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M9 12h6m-6 4h6m2 5H7a2 2 0 01-2-2V5a2 2 0 012-2h5.586a1 1 0 01.707.293l5.414 5.414a1 1 0 01.293.707V19a2 2 0 01-2 2z"/></svg></span><span class="ft-name">typography.md</span></div>
                    <div class="ft-row ft-file-row"><span class="ft-icon ft-md-icon"><svg width="13" height="13" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M9 12h6m-6 4h6m2 5H7a2 2 0 01-2-2V5a2 2 0 012-2h5.586a1 1 0 01.707.293l5.414 5.414a1 1 0 01.293.707V19a2 2 0 01-2 2z"/></svg></span><span class="ft-name">spacing.md</span></div>
