                  <td>Chip</td>
                  <td>Filter/action/input types, dismissible, icon slots</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><code>accordion.md</code></td>
                  <td>Accordion</td>
                  <td>Single vs. multi expand, controlled/uncontrolled, animation</td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td><code>status-indicator.md</code></td>
                  <td>Status Indicator</td>
                  <td>Semantic statuses, pulse animation, inline vs. standalone</td>
                </tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>

            <h3 id="spec-template" class="doc-h3">Spec file template</h3>
            <p class="doc-section-subtitle">Every spec file follows this exact structure. Consistency lets LLMs locate the right section without guessing.</p>

            <div class="code-block">
<span class="code-comment"># component-name.md</span>

<span class="code-key">## Overview</span>
One-paragraph description. What it is, when to use it, primary use case.

<span class="code-key">## Anatomy</span>
Named breakdown of each visual and functional part.
- Root / wrapper
- Trigger (if applicable)
- Content / body
- Arrow / indicator (if applicable)
- Close control (if applicable)

<span class="code-key">## Variants</span>
| Prop      | Values                  | Default  |
|-----------|-------------------------|----------|
| theme     | dark \| light \| red    | dark     |
| placement | top \| bottom \| left … | top      |

<span class="code-key">## Token mapping</span>
| Token                      | CSS variable              | Role              |
|----------------------------|---------------------------|-------------------|
| Background                 | --tt-bg                   | Surface fill      |
| Text                       | --tt-text                 | Label color       |

<span class="code-key">## Usage rules</span>
- When to use
- When NOT to use
- Accessibility requirements (ARIA roles, keyboard nav)

<span class="code-key">## Do / Don't</span>
✅ Use semantic tokens for all colors
❌ Do not hardcode hex values in component styles

<span class="code-key">## Code example</span>
&lt;!-- Correct usage --&gt;
&lt;div class="tt-root" data-theme="dark" data-placement="top"&gt;…&lt;/div&gt;
            </div>
            -->
          </div>

          <hr class="doc-divider" />

          <!-- Architecture -->
          <div class="doc-section">
            <h2 id="architecture" class="doc-section-title">Architecture</h2>
            <p class="doc-section-subtitle">Prism uses a three-layer token architecture. Each layer depends on the one below it — changes at the upstream level cascade automatically.</p>

            <div style="margin-top: 24px; display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 16px;">
              <div style="padding: 24px 28px; background: var(--prism-surface); border: 1px solid var(--prism-border); border-radius: 14px; border-left: 4px solid #8b5cf6; transition: all 0.2s ease;">
                <div style="display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: space-between; margin-bottom: 10px;">
                  <span style="font-size: 13px; font-weight: 700; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.1em; color: #8b5cf6;">Layer 1 — Upstream / Primitive</span>
                  <code style="font-family:monospace; font-size:12px; padding:2px 8px; border-radius:6px; background:rgba(139,92,246,0.1); color:#8b5cf6;">prism-tokens.css</code>
                </div>
                <p style="font-size: 14px; color: var(--prism-text-muted); line-height: 1.6; margin-bottom: 12px;">Raw value definitions — the full palette, base spacing scale, radius scale, and elevation values. These are never referenced directly in components.</p>
                <div class="code-block" style="margin-top: 0; padding: 16px 20px; font-size: 12.5px;">
--color-blue-600: <span class="code-string">#2563eb</span>;
--space-4: <span class="code-string">16px</span>;
--radius-md: <span class="code-string">8px</span>;
                </div>
              </div>

              <div style="display: flex; justify-content: center; align-items: center; height: 28px;">
                <svg width="16" height="28" viewBox="0 0 16 28" fill="none" style="color: var(--prism-text-muted); opacity: 0.4;"><path d="M8 0v20M1 14l7 7 7-7" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/></svg>
              </div>

              <div style="padding: 24px 28px; background: var(--prism-surface); border: 1px solid var(--prism-border); border-radius: 14px; border-left: 4px solid var(--prism-violet); transition: all 0.2s ease;">
                <div style="display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: space-between; margin-bottom: 10px;">
                  <span style="font-size: 13px; font-weight: 700; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.1em; color: var(--prism-violet);">Layer 2 — Semantic / Project</span>
                  <code style="font-family:monospace; font-size:12px; padding:2px 8px; border-radius:6px; background:rgba(37,99,235,0.1); color:var(--prism-violet);">project-tokens.css</code>
                </div>
                <p style="font-size: 14px; color: var(--prism-text-muted); line-height: 1.6; margin-bottom: 12px;">Intent-mapped aliases. These reference Layer 1 values and give them semantic meaning — surface, text, border — that components consume. Light/dark themes are defined here via <code style="font-family:monospace; font-size:12px;">[data-theme]</code> overrides.</p>
                <div class="code-block" style="margin-top: 0; padding: 16px 20px; font-size: 12.5px;">
--prism-violet:      var(--color-blue-600);
--prism-text:        rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.92);
--prism-surface:     rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.05);
--prism-border:      rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.07);

[data-theme=<span class="code-string">"light"</span>] {
  --prism-text:      <span class="code-string">#1a1a2e</span>;
  --prism-surface:   rgba(37, 99, 235, 0.028);
}
                </div>
              </div>

              <div style="display: flex; justify-content: center; align-items: center; height: 28px;">
                <svg width="16" height="28" viewBox="0 0 16 28" fill="none" style="color: var(--prism-text-muted); opacity: 0.4;"><path d="M8 0v20M1 14l7 7 7-7" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/></svg>
              </div>

              <div style="padding: 24px 28px; background: var(--prism-surface); border: 1px solid var(--prism-border); border-radius: 14px; border-left: 4px solid #06b6d4; transition: all 0.2s ease;">
                <div style="display: flex; align-items: center; justify-content: space-between; margin-bottom: 10px;">
                  <span style="font-size: 13px; font-weight: 700; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.1em; color: #06b6d4;">Layer 3 — Component</span>
                  <code style="font-family:monospace; font-size:12px; padding:2px 8px; border-radius:6px; background:rgba(6,182,212,0.1); color:#06b6d4;">component.css</code>
                </div>
                <p style="font-size: 14px; color: var(--prism-text-muted); line-height: 1.6; margin-bottom: 12px;">Component-scoped aliases that map to Layer 2 semantic tokens. Each component only knows about its own token namespace. This makes theming and overriding predictable — you never touch raw values.</p>
                <div class="code-block" style="margin-top: 0; padding: 16px 20px; font-size: 12.5px;">
<span class="code-comment">/* Tooltip component tokens */</span>
.tt-root {
  --tt-bg:      var(--prism-surface);
  --tt-text:    var(--prism-text);
  --tt-border:  var(--prism-border);
  --tt-radius:  var(--radius-md);
}
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>

            <h3 id="token-resolution" class="doc-h3">Token resolution order</h3>
            <p class="doc-section-subtitle">When a component renders, CSS resolves tokens in this order — from the most specific override back to the root primitive.</p>

            <div class="code-block">
<span class="code-comment">/* Resolution chain for a Tooltip background in light mode */</span>

.tt-body { background: var(--tt-bg); }
           <span class="code-comment">↓ resolves to</span>
--tt-bg: var(--prism-surface)
         <span class="code-comment">↓ resolves to  (light mode override)</span>
--prism-surface: rgba(37, 99, 235, 0.028)
            </div>

            <h3 id="llm-context-order" class="doc-h3">What to feed the LLM — and in what order</h3>
            <p class="doc-section-subtitle">Context order matters. Feed layers from most-general to most-specific so the model builds understanding before it sees component details.</p>

            <ol class="step-list">
              <li class="step-item">
                <div class="step-num">1</div>
                <div class="step-content">
                  <div class="step-title">Layer 2 tokens — <code style="font-family:monospace; font-size:12.5px;">prism-tokens.css</code></div>
                  <div class="step-desc">The full semantic token map. This is the most important file — it defines the complete vocabulary the LLM should use for every color, spacing, and surface decision.</div>
                </div>
              </li>
              <li class="step-item">
                <div class="step-num">2</div>
                <div class="step-content">
                  <div class="step-title">Relevant foundation spec(s)</div>
                  <div class="step-desc">If the task involves layout: include <code style="font-family:monospace; font-size:12.5px;">spacing.md</code> and <code style="font-family:monospace; font-size:12.5px;">grid.md</code>. If it involves color decisions: include <code style="font-family:monospace; font-size:12.5px;">color.md</code>. Don't include all foundation files — excess context dilutes focus.</div>
                </div>
              </li>
              <li class="step-item">
                <div class="step-num">3</div>
                <div class="step-content">
                  <div class="step-title">Relevant component spec(s) from <code style="font-family:monospace; font-size:12.5px;">specs/</code></div>
                  <div class="step-desc">The specific component spec files needed for the task. Include only what's needed — if building a form: <code style="font-family:monospace; font-size:12.5px;">input.md</code>, <code style="font-family:monospace; font-size:12.5px;">button.md</code>, <code style="font-family:monospace; font-size:12.5px;">label.md</code>.</div>
                </div>
              </li>
              <li class="step-item">
                <div class="step-num">4</div>
                <div class="step-content">
                  <div class="step-title">Your task prompt with explicit constraints</div>
                  <div class="step-desc">Write the task after the context. Start with: <em>"Using only Prism tokens and the components defined in the spec files above, build…"</em></div>
                </div>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </div>

          <hr class="doc-divider" />

          <!-- The Setup -->
          <div class="doc-section">
            <h2 id="the-setup" class="doc-section-title">The setup — six steps</h2>
            <p class="doc-section-subtitle">Configure your LLM to use Prism by default. This works with Claude, ChatGPT, Copilot, Cursor, or any context-aware AI tool.</p>

            <ol class="step-list">
              <li class="step-item">
                <div class="step-num">1</div>
                <div class="step-content">
                  <div class="step-title">Attach the token file to your system prompt</div>
                  <div class="step-desc">Paste the full contents of <code style="font-family:monospace; font-size:12.5px;">prism-tokens.css</code> into the system prompt or IDE context. This gives the model the full token vocabulary before it writes a single line.</div>
                </div>
              </li>
              <li class="step-item">
                <div class="step-num">2</div>
                <div class="step-content">
                  <div class="step-title">Include the relevant component spec file(s)</div>
                  <div class="step-desc">When building a feature involving Tooltip, attach <code style="font-family:monospace; font-size:12.5px;">tooltip.md</code>. For a form, attach <code style="font-family:monospace; font-size:12.5px;">input.md</code>, <code style="font-family:monospace; font-size:12.5px;">button.md</code>, and <code style="font-family:monospace; font-size:12.5px;">label.md</code>. Only include relevant specs — excess context dilutes focus.</div>
                </div>
              </li>
              <li class="step-item">
                <div class="step-num">3</div>
                <div class="step-content">
                  <div class="step-title">Write an explicit constraint in the prompt</div>
                  <div class="step-desc">Start every prompt with: <em>"Use only Prism design tokens (see attached). Do not hardcode hex values, px values, or custom class names outside the spec."</em> Explicit constraints outperform implicit ones.</div>
                </div>
              </li>
              <li class="step-item">
                <div class="step-num">4</div>
                <div class="step-content">
                  <div class="step-title">Review and audit generated output</div>
                  <div class="step-desc">Run the audit script against the generated code before accepting it. Flag violations back to the LLM: <em>"This uses #1e293b — use --prism-text instead."</em> Iterative correction tightens future outputs.</div>
                </div>
              </li>
              <li class="step-item">
                <div class="step-num">5</div>
                <div class="step-content">
                  <div class="step-title">Add audit to CI</div>
                  <div class="step-desc">Wire the audit script into your CI pipeline. PRs that introduce hardcoded values or off-spec components fail automatically. This enforces the system without manual review.</div>
                </div>
              </li>
              <li class="step-item">
                <div class="step-num">6</div>
                <div class="step-content">
                  <div class="step-title">Keep spec files in sync with components</div>
                  <div class="step-desc">When you update a component's API, update its spec file in the same PR. Stale spec files cause LLM drift — the model follows the spec, not the code, so outdated specs produce outdated output.</div>
                </div>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </div>

          <hr class="doc-divider" />

          <!-- Results -->
          <div class="doc-section">
            <h2 id="results" class="doc-section-title">What this approach achieves</h2>
            <p class="doc-section-subtitle">Teams adopting this three-layer method consistently see the following improvements over baseline LLM-generated UI.</p>

            <div class="stat-grid">
              <div class="stat-card">
                <div class="stat-number">0</div>
                <div class="stat-label">Hardcoded hex values in AI-generated code after enforcement</div>
              </div>
              <div class="stat-card">
                <div class="stat-number">64+</div>
                <div class="stat-label">Component spec files covering the full Prism component set</div>
              </div>
              <div class="stat-card">
                <div class="stat-number">230+</div>
                <div class="stat-label">Semantic tokens available for LLM context injection</div>
              </div>
            </div>

            <h3 id="before-after" class="doc-h3">Before vs. after</h3>
            <table class="result-table" style="margin-top: 20px;">
              <thead>
                <tr>
                  <th>Metric</th>
                  <th>Without spec context</th>
                  <th>With Prism spec context</th>
                </tr>
              </thead>
              <tbody>
                <tr>
                  <td>Token usage in generated code</td>
                  <td><span class="badge-before">~10%</span></td>
                  <td><span class="badge-after">&gt;95%</span></td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>Hardcoded color values</td>
                  <td><span class="badge-before">Frequent</span></td>
                  <td><span class="badge-after">Near zero</span></td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>Component API compliance</td>
                  <td><span class="badge-before">Inconsistent</span></td>
                  <td><span class="badge-after">Reliable</span></td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>Dark mode support</td>
                  <td><span class="badge-before">Missing or broken</span></td>
                  <td><span class="badge-after">Automatic via tokens</span></td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>Accessibility attributes</td>
                  <td><span class="badge-before">Often missing</span></td>
                  <td><span class="badge-after">Included per spec</span></td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td>Design review pass rate</td>
                  <td><span class="badge-before">Low</span></td>
                  <td><span class="badge-after">High</span></td>
                </tr>
              </tbody>
            </table>
          </div>

          <hr class="doc-divider" />

          <!-- FAQs -->
          <div class="doc-section">
            <h2 id="faqs" class="doc-section-title">Frequently asked questions</h2>

            <div class="faq-list">
              <div class="faq-item">
                <div class="faq-q">Does this work with all LLMs?</div>
                <div class="faq-a">Yes. The approach works with any model that accepts a system prompt or context window — Claude, GPT-4o, Gemini, Copilot, Cursor, etc. Larger context windows (100k+) let you include more spec files simultaneously.</div>
              </div>
              <div class="faq-item">
                <div class="faq-q">What if the LLM ignores my token file?</div>
                <div class="faq-a">Add an explicit instruction: <em>"You MUST use only the tokens defined in the token file. Any hex value not listed there is a violation."</em> Constraint language is more effective than descriptive language with LLMs.</div>
              </div>
              <div class="faq-item">
                <div class="faq-q">How granular should spec files be?</div>
                <div class="faq-a">Aim for one spec file per component variant group. A Tooltip spec covers all tooltip variants. A Button spec covers primary, secondary, ghost, and danger. Splitting by variant creates too many files; merging everything creates files too large to parse reliably.</div>
              </div>
              <div class="faq-item">
                <div class="faq-q">Should spec files include code samples?</div>
                <div class="faq-a">Yes — short, complete code samples are the single most effective addition. LLMs pattern-match on examples more reliably than they follow prose descriptions. Include one "correct" usage example and one "incorrect" example per component.</div>
              </div>
              <div class="faq-item">
                <div class="faq-q">What about Figma variables — do those count as the token layer?</div>
                <div class="faq-a">Figma variables are the design-side token layer. The LLM-facing token layer should be a CSS or JSON file that maps those same decisions to code-consumable variable names. Keep them in sync — a Figma variable rename should be reflected in the token file.</div>
              </div>
              <div class="faq-item">
                <div class="faq-q">Who is responsible for keeping spec files current?</div>
                <div class="faq-a">The component owner — the same person who updates the component source code. Spec updates should be mandatory in component PRs. Treat a stale spec file with the same severity as a broken test.</div>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <hr class="doc-divider" />

          <!-- Closing Principle -->
          <div class="doc-section">
            <div style="padding: 32px 40px; background: linear-gradient(135deg, rgba(37,99,235,0.06) 0%, rgba(6,182,212,0.06) 100%); border: 1px solid rgba(37,99,235,0.15); border-radius: 16px; text-align: center;">
              <h2 id="principle" style="font-size: 24px; font-weight: 700; color: var(--prism-text); margin-bottom: 12px;">Principle</h2>
              <p style="font-size: 17px; color: var(--prism-text-muted); line-height: 1.7; max-width: 640px; margin: 0 auto;">An LLM is only as good as the context you give it. <strong style="color: var(--prism-text);">Spec files make components legible.</strong> <strong style="color: var(--prism-text);">Tokens make intent portable.</strong> <strong style="color: var(--prism-text);">Audit scripts make compliance enforced.</strong> Together, they let Prism be the design system for both humans and AI.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <!-- Feedback banner -->
          <div class="feedback-banner" style="display: none;">
            <div>
              <div class="fb-text">Help us improve this page</div>
              <div class="fb-sub">Share your feedback to help shape the LLM Reference documentation.</div>
            </div>
            <div style="display: flex; gap: 12px;">
              <button class="feedback-btn primary" onclick="window.open('https://cliq.zoho.in/company/60002085329/channels/prismdesignsystembyuemssupportfeedback','_blank')">Give Feedback</button>
            </div>
          </div>

        </div>

        <aside class="toc-sidebar">
          <h4 class="toc-heading">On this page</h4>
          <ul class="toc-nav" id="toc-nav"></ul>
        </aside>
      </div>
    </main>
  </div>

  <script>
    let _tocObserver = null;
    function buildTOC() {
      const tocList = document.getElementById('toc-nav');
      if (!tocList) return;
      tocList.innerHTML = '';
      const inner = document.querySelector('.main-content-inner');
      if (!inner) return;
      const headings = inner.querySelectorAll('h2[id], h3[id]');
      const sections = [];
      headings.forEach(h => {
        if (h.style.display === 'none') return;
        const li = document.createElement('li');
        const a = document.createElement('a');
        a.href = '#' + h.id;
        a.className = 'toc-link';
        let text = Array.from(h.childNodes).filter(n => n.nodeType === 3).map(n => n.textContent).join('').trim();
        if (!text) text = h.innerText.replace(/^\d+\.\s*/, '');
        a.textContent = text;
        if (h.tagName === 'H3') { a.style.paddingLeft = '16px'; a.style.fontSize = '12.5px'; }
        a.addEventListener('click', e => { e.preventDefault(); document.getElementById(h.id).scrollIntoView({ behavior: 'smooth', block: 'start' }); });
        li.appendChild(a);
        tocList.appendChild(li);
        sections.push(h);
      });
      if (_tocObserver) _tocObserver.disconnect();
      _tocObserver = new IntersectionObserver(entries => {
        entries.forEach(entry => {
          if (entry.isIntersecting) {
            const id = entry.target.getAttribute('id');
            document.querySelectorAll('.toc-link').forEach(link => {
              link.classList.toggle('active', link.getAttribute('href') === '#' + id);
            });
          }
        });
      }, { rootMargin: '-80px 0px -60% 0px', threshold: 0 });
      sections.forEach(s => _tocObserver.observe(s));
    }
    buildTOC();

    // File tree expand/collapse
    document.querySelectorAll('.ft-folder-row').forEach(row => {
      row.addEventListener('click', () => {
        const id = row.getAttribute('data-tree');
        const subtree = document.getElementById(id);
        if (!subtree) return;
        const open = subtree.classList.toggle('open');
        row.classList.toggle('open', open);
      });
    });
    // Open specs/ by default
    const specsRow = document.querySelector('[data-tree="specs"]');
    const specsTree = document.getElementById('specs');
    if (specsRow && specsTree) { specsTree.classList.add('open'); specsRow.classList.add('open'); }
    const scriptsRow = document.querySelector('[data-tree="scripts"]');
    const scriptsTree = document.getElementById('scripts');
    if (scriptsRow && scriptsTree) { scriptsTree.classList.add('open'); scriptsRow.classList.add('open'); }

    const themeToggle = document.getElementById('themeToggle');
    const moonIcon = document.getElementById('moonIcon');
    const sunIcon = document.getElementById('sunIcon');
    const currentTheme = localStorage.getItem('theme') || 'light';
    if (currentTheme === 'dark') {
      document.documentElement.removeAttribute('data-theme');
      moonIcon.style.display = 'block'; sunIcon.style.display = 'none';
    }
    themeToggle.addEventListener('click', () => {
      let theme = document.documentElement.getAttribute('data-theme');
      if (theme === 'light') {
        document.documentElement.removeAttribute('data-theme');
        localStorage.setItem('theme', 'dark');
        moonIcon.style.display = 'block'; sunIcon.style.display = 'none';
      } else {
        document.documentElement.setAttribute('data-theme', 'light');
        localStorage.setItem('theme', 'light');
        moonIcon.style.display = 'none'; sunIcon.style.display = 'block';
      }
    });
  </script>

